I have successfully implemented comprehensive E2E tests for the OpenPrint Dashboard using Playwright with the Page Object Model pattern. Here's a summary of what was created:

## Page Object Model Classes (`pages/`)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `BasePage.ts` | Common navigation, authentication, and utility methods |
| `DashboardPage.ts` | Dashboard stats, recent activity, environmental reports |
| `AuthPage.ts` | Login, registration, OIDC, SAML authentication flows |
| `JobsPage.ts` | Job creation, filtering, status changes |
| `PrintersPage.ts` | Printer management, discovery, configuration |
| `AnalyticsPage.ts` | Metrics, charts, audit logs |
| `SettingsPage.ts` | Profile, security, preferences management |
| `SecurePrintPage.ts` | PIN-based job release |
| `QuotasPage.ts` | Cost tracking and quotas |
| `PoliciesPage.ts` | Print policy engine management |
| `Microsoft365Page.ts` | OneDrive, SharePoint, Outlook integration |
| `CompliancePage.ts` | FedRAMP/HIPAA compliance reports |

## Test Infrastructure (`factories/`, `fixtures/`)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `TestDataFactory.ts` | Generate realistic test data (users, jobs, printers, policies) |
| `visual-regression.spec.ts` | UI consistency and screenshot comparison tests |
| `websocket-mock.ts` | WebSocket mocking for real-time update tests |

## New Test Suites (`tests/`)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `microsoft-365.spec.ts` | Microsoft 365 integration tests |
| `compliance.spec.ts` | FedRAMP/HIPAA compliance testing |
| `realtime-updates.spec.ts` | WebSocket real-time update tests |

## Running Tests

```bash
# Run all E2E tests
npm run test:e2e

# Run specific test suites
npx playwright test tests/microsoft-365.spec.ts
npx playwright test tests/compliance.spec.ts
npx playwright test tests/realtime-updates.spec.ts

# Run with UI mode
npm run test:e2e:ui

# Visual regression tests
npx playwright test fixtures/visual-regression.spec.ts
```
